# Using Workers (Subagents) to Split Tasks

Use the **worker/subagent** feature to split work across separate agents when it makes the response faster or more thorough.

## When to launch a worker

- **Parallel work**: Multiple independent steps (e.g. explore codebase in one place + run tests in another). Launch 2–4 workers in parallel when steps don’t depend on each other.
- **Broad exploration**: “How does X work?”, “Where is Y?”, “What’s the structure of Z?” — use an **explore** worker with thoroughness “quick”, “medium”, or “very thorough”.
- **Shell/commands**: Git, installs, builds, scripts — use a **shell** worker so the main agent stays focused on code/design.
- **Research or multi-step work**: Deep search, multi-file refactors, or follow-up steps — use a **generalPurpose** worker with a clear, self-contained task description.

## When not to use a worker

- **Single, narrow question** (e.g. “Where is ClientError defined?”) — use grep/read directly.
- **Quick, few-step tasks** — handle in the main turn.
- **Tasks that need your current context** — don’t delegate if the worker wouldn’t have enough info.

## How to use

- **One message, multiple workers**: Prefer one user turn with several worker launches (e.g. explore + shell) when tasks are independent.
- **Describe the task fully**: Workers don’t see the rest of the chat; put all needed context (paths, goals, constraints) in the worker prompt.
- **Say what you want back**: Specify what the worker should return (e.g. “list of file paths”, “summary of how auth works”) so you can use it in the main reply.

Split tasks across workers when it clearly improves speed or quality; otherwise keep the work in the main agent.
